SENIOR SPOTLIGHT - 6/6/2020

Emma Pankalla

"Emma has thoroughly loved growing up in Philomath and being part of this smaller community affording the opportunity to be involved in many PHS activities and ASB. Like many of her classmates and teammates, much of her time has been devoted to the successful athletic programs PHS continually produces. Beginning with PYAC and AYSO to taking third in state in Volleyball and being ranked first in state in basketball throughout her senior year. Emma earned first and second team all league honors all four years in basketball and was voted to the 2nd team all-state team this year. Emma‚Äôs teammates voted her the MVP for three consecutive years and she holds the school record for most assists. Emma plans to attend OSU in pursuit of a career where she can work with people to accomplish great things."

Parents can order their student's supplies online and the supplies will ship directly to your student's school.

If you have any questions about school supplies and this process please feel free to e-mail Mrs. Crocker @ molly.crocker@philomath.k12.or.us

SENIOR SPOTLIGHT - 5/25/2020

Joelle Berger

"Joelle is excited for graduation, no matter what form it takes. She'll be driving a combine over the summer and then starting Seattle Pacific University in the Fall to study Nursing with a Spanish minor. Senior year hasn't been what anyone expected and she's sad to not get a chance to finish it with her teachers, coach and friends, but is making the most of it. The year has been full of ups and downs with an awesome volleyball season, followed by shoulder surgery, quarantine, being chosen as a Valedictorian, and wrapping up with a 4.0 GPA. Many of her favorite memories involve volleyball, especially pre-game huddles and singing. We're so proud of her and excited to see what her future holds. We know that, at the very least, she'll travel to amazing places, help people, keep a great attitude, and adopt ALL the puppers."

"Ben has attended Philomath schools since Kindergarten. During this time, basketball and soccer played major roles for him and for his family. Ben started playing basketball in the 3rd grade through PYAC and continued until his senior year. Ben and his Warrior teammates finished their 2019-20 basketball season in triumphant style‚Äîfinishing with a number 2 ranking in the state! Although the soccer season did not finish with quite the bang, he was listed second team all decade. Ben will attend Oregon State University in fall 2020 and major in Biology with a focus on Marine Biology. For his senior project, he got the opportunity to work in one of the most respected marine labs at the OSU campus. He travelled to the coast to collected biological samples for this lab and it made quite an impression. His family is so proud of him, not only for his accomplishments but of what he has become‚Äîa mature, smart, and strong individual that we know has an exciting future. Congratulations, Ben!"

post_text:
MESSAGE FROM PHS STUDENTS

Greetings, Warriors!

We‚Äôre thrilled to spread the word about a project started by a few students at PHS called Charge Forward. The goal of the organization is to give computers to students in need, and close the rapidly growing gap between students with ample technology access, and those without it. The program is entirely free, and once a computer is given to a student, it is theirs to keep, no strings attached. The process to donate is very simple. Simply find unused computers, cables, or whatever unused technology you‚Äôd be willing to give to the cause (even if it‚Äôs broken!), and visit
/chargeforward.tech/donate. Once you submit a donation, a member of their team will meet you wherever is convenient for you, and collect your donation. Afterwards, they clean all information (and potential germs!) from the tech, to protect your private information, and after the process is complete, another student in need gets access to infinite learning opportunities.

Visit https://www.chargeforward.tech/ to learn more.

The lights will come on Friday nights at 20:20 military time in honor of our seniors (8:20 pm) and will light up the stadium for twenty minutes. This will happen every Friday for the entire closure.

This is modeled after the Colorado Be the Light Movement.

Dear Philomath School District Families,

We hope you have a relaxing winter break and take the time to renew your energy after a long year and decade!

We know that the holidays can be stressful for many and want to share with you a resource for parents and students. If you find yourself struggling with stress, depression, anxiety, or other issues over the break, please reach out to someone. The Crisis Text Line is a free resource to everyone ‚Äì Text OREGON to 741741 for 24/7 confidential support.

Happy Holidays. We look forward to seeing you all in 2020.

Dear Philomath School District Families,

We hope you have a relaxing winter break and take the time to renew your energy after a long year and decade!

We know that the holidays can be stressful for many and want to share with you a resource for parents and students. If you find yourself struggling with stress, depression, anxiety, or other issues over the break, please reach out to someone. The Crisis Text Line is a free resource to everyone ‚Äì Text OREGON to 741741 for 24/7 confidential support.

Happy Holidays. We look forward to seeing you all in 2020.

post_text: Thanks to the City of Philomath for posting this great news!
shared_text:
City of Philomath, Oregon
July 29, 2019 at 4:22 PM ¬∑

Groundbreaking: Philomath Tennis Courts.
Crews arrived to prepare the site of the future tennis courts at the High School this morning. The courts will be located between the varsity softball field and Philomath City Park. The City and School District have worked together to bring tennis courts back to Philomath, with primary use granted to the schools and tennis team, and the public able to access the courts when not in use by the schools. Pictured here is Mayor Eric Niemann, Contractor Dennis Gibson, School District Facilities Director Joey DiGiovannangelo, Park Advisory Board Chair Dale Collins, and School District Director of Finance and Operations Bill Mancuso who met briefly to look over the site layout.

The City and School District have worked together to bring tennis courts back to Philomath, with primary use granted to the schools and tennis team, and the public able to access the courts when not in use by the schools. Pictured here is Mayor Eric Niemann, Contractor Dennis Gibson, School District Facilities Director Joey DiGiovannangelo, Park Advisory Board Chair Dale Collins, and School District Director of Finance and Operations Bill Mancuso who met briefly to look over the site layout.

post_text:
Thanks to Lyn Kawai, our English Language Coordinator, our students are creating this fantastic mural! Here are a few pics of the project, painted by PES, PMS and PHS students (some parents and teachers, too!). This will hang at PES near where the kids head out to recess.

Esteban, our visiting artist, is doing a great job! About 25-30 people, mostly students from 2nd grade to 12th grade, are working together on the project. The mural depicts various birds of prey including the Peregrine falcon but also non falcons such as the dove flying against a sunset of vibrant colors full of clouds.

post_text: Serving Philomath School District as superintendent for the last four years has been my privilege and honor. It will be difficult for me to take this step as I will so miss all of you, and I know the work we have accomplished has changed the lives of many students. post_text:
"I wanted to share with you another example of just how wonderful our Philomath students are. I have always believed they are some of the most awesome students ever but witnessed it again this last week.
It was a dark and foggy night and I was leaving work when I heard three students laughing and bouncing a basketball in front of the district office. My heart was happy hearing them have so much fun together. I continued down the sidewalk and over the curb to my car with my walker when I hear one of them say, 'excuse me‚Ä¶.do you need some help?' I teared up and said 'thank you, but I appreciate you offering.'
It makes my heart happy that in this world of 'it‚Äôs all about me' our Philomath students are out there thinking of others. They never disappoint me!

I wish I would have asked their names so I could thank them personally!"

With a happy heart,
Diana Matlock
Special Programs Administrative Assistant

post_text: We are so grateful to the Benton Community Foundation for their contribution of $734,000 from the Kitty Nitka Pool Fund to help keep the Clemens Community Pool open for another 10 years! #pool #swim #community #philomath #corvallis #oregon #smalltown #swimming #kittynitka #watersafety #rexandethelclemens
text: We are so grateful to the Benton Community Foundation for their contribution of $734,000 from the Kitty Nitka Pool Fund to help keep the Clemens Community Pool open for another 10 years! #pool #swim #community #philomath #corvallis #oregon #smalltown #swimming #kittynitka #watersafety #rexandethelclemens

post_text: We are so grateful to the Benton Community Foundation for their contribution of $734,000 from the Kitty Nitka Pool Fund to help keep the Clemens Community Pool open for another 10 years! #pool #swim #community #philomath #corvallis #oregon #smalltown #swimming #kittynitka #watersafety #rexandethelclemens
shared_text:
Benton Community Foundation
October 16, 2018 at 3:56 PM ¬∑

Clemens Community Pool has been a treasured resource for Philomath, and across Benton County, since 1960. Many of you have been concerned the pool would have to close due to a lack of funding for critical infrastructure needs. We're proud to announce that the Benton Community Foundation is making a transformational gift of $734,000 to keep the Clemens Community Pool open. Our contribution is possible thanks to the Nitka family's Philomath Community Pool Fund. With this gift, the pool will be able to remain open and continue to serve as a place for all to gather, exercise, and safely learn to swim.

#Corvallis #Philomath Corvallis Gazette-Times Corvallis-Benton County Public Library Visit Corvallis City of Philomath, Oregon Philomath Area Chamber Commerce Philomath School District 17J Clemens Community Pool in Philomath Rotary Club of Philomath, Oregon USA The Oregon Community Foundation Spirit Mountain Community Fund The Ford Family Foundation
